SIMPLE: insertion
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Insertion
<hw>In*ser"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>insertio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>insertion</ets>. See
<er>Insert</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of inserting; <as>as, the <ex>insertion</ex>
of scions in stocks; the <ex>insertion</ex> of words or passages in
writings.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The condition or mode of being inserted or attached;
<as>as, the <ex>insertion</ex> of stamens in a calyx</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is set in or inserted, such as a word or
passage in a composition, or a narrow strip of embroidered lace, muslin,
or cambric; <as>as, there were numerous <ex>insertions</ex> and
corrections to the first draft</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The point or part by which a
muscle or tendon is attached to the part to be moved; -- in
contradistinction to its <contr>origin</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Epigynous insertion</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the
insertion of stamens upon the ovary.</cd> -- <col><b>Hypogynous
insertion</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>insertion beneath the
ovary.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inserve</ent>⟦br⟧
